  "local_port": 34810,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I cook manchurian?",
  "response": "Sure! Manchurian is a popular Indo-Chinese dish that comes in various forms, the most common being **Vegetable (Gobi) Manchurian** and **Chicken Manchurian**. Below, you'll find detailed recipes for both versions. You can choose the one that suits your preference or try both!\n\n---\n\n## Vegetable (Gobi) Manchurian Recipe\n\n### **Ingredients**\n\n#### For the Manchurian Balls:\n- **Cauliflower (Gobi)**: 1 medium-sized, cut into florets\n- **All-Purpose Flour (Maida)**: 1/4 cup\n- **Cornstarch**: 2 tablespoons\n- **Ginger-Garlic Paste**: 1 teaspoon\n- **Green Chili (optional)**: 1, finely chopped\n- **Salt**: to taste\n- **Black Pepper Powder**: 1/2 teaspoon\n- **Water**: as needed\n- **Oil**: for deep frying\n\n#### For the Sauce:\n- **Oil**: 2 tablespoons\n- **Garlic Cloves**: 4-5, finely chopped\n- **Ginger**: 1-inch piece, finely chopped\n- **Green Chili**: 1, slit or finely chopped\n- **Spring Onions**: 2-3, chopped (separate green and white parts)\n- **Bell Peppers**: 1 medium (capsicum), diced\n- **Soy Sauce**: 2 tablespoons\n- **Tomato Ketchup**: 2 tablespoons\n- **Red Chili Sauce (optional)**: 1 tablespoon\n- **Vinegar**: 1 teaspoon\n- **Sugar**: 1 teaspoon\n- **Salt**: to taste\n- **Black Pepper Powder**: 1/2 teaspoon\n- **Cornstarch**: 1 tablespoon\n- **Water**: 1/2 cup\n- **Spring Onion Greens**: for garnish\n\n### **Instructions**\n\n#### Making the Manchurian Balls:\n1. **Prepare Cauliflower**: Blanch the cauliflower florets by boiling them in water with a pinch of salt for 2-3 minutes. Drain and pat dry with a kitchen towel to remove excess moisture.\n\n2. **Prepare Batter**: In a mixing bowl, combine all-purpose flour, cornstarch, ginger-garlic paste, chopped green chili, salt, and black pepper. Gradually add water to form a thick batter.\n\n3. **Coat Cauliflower**: Dip each cauliflower floret into the batter, ensuring it's well-coated.\n\n4. **Deep Fry**: Heat oil in a deep pan or kadai over medium heat. Once hot, deep fry the batter-coated florets until they turn golden brown and crispy. Remove and drain on paper towels. Set aside.\n\n#### Preparing the Sauce:\n1. **Make Cornstarch Slurry**: In a small bowl, mix cornstarch with 2 tablespoons of water to make a smooth slurry. Set aside.\n\n2. **Saut\u00e9 Aromatics**: In a pan or wok, heat 2 tablespoons of oil over medium heat. Add chopped garlic, ginger, and green chili. Saut\u00e9 for about 30 seconds until fragrant.\n\n3. **Add Vegetables**: Add the white parts of the spring onions and diced bell peppers. Stir-fry for 2-3 minutes until they are slightly tender but still retain crunch.\n\n4. **Add Sauces and Spices**: Stir in soy sauce, tomato ketchup, red chili sauce (if using), vinegar, sugar, salt, and black pepper powder. Mix well.\n\n5. **Add Slurry**: Pour the cornstarch slurry into the pan, stirring continuously to avoid lumps. Cook the sauce until it thickens to your desired consistency.\n\n6. **Combine with Manchurian Balls**: Add the fried cauliflower florets to the sauce and toss gently to coat them evenly.\n\n7. **Garnish and Serve**: Garnish with the green parts of spring onions. Serve hot as an appetizer or with fried rice or noodles as a main dish.\n\n---\n\n## Chicken Manchurian Recipe\n\n### **Ingredients**\n\n#### For the Chicken Balls:\n- **Boneless Chicken**: 500 grams, cut into bite-sized pieces\n- **All-Purpose Flour (Maida)**: 1/4 cup\n- **Cornstarch**: 2 tablespoons\n- **Egg**: 1, beaten\n- **Ginger-Garlic Paste**: 1 teaspoon\n- **Salt**: to taste\n- **Black Pepper Powder**: 1/2 teaspoon\n- **Soy Sauce**: 1 tablespoon\n- **Oil**: for deep frying\n\n#### For the Sauce:\n- **Oil**: 2 tablespoons\n- **Garlic Cloves**: 4-5, finely chopped\n- **Ginger**: 1-inch piece, finely chopped\n- **Green Chili**: 1, slit or finely chopped\n- **Spring Onions**: 2-3, chopped (separate green and white parts)\n- **Bell Peppers**: 1 medium (capsicum), diced\n- **Soy Sauce**: 2 tablespoons\n- **Tomato Ketchup**: 2 tablespoons\n- **Red Chili Sauce (optional)**: 1 tablespoon\n- **Vinegar**: 1 teaspoon\n- **Sugar**: 1 teaspoon\n- **Salt**: to taste\n- **Black Pepper Powder**: 1/2 teaspoon\n- **Cornstarch**: 1 tablespoon\n- **Water**: 1/2 cup\n- **Spring Onion Greens**: for garnish\n\n### **Instructions**\n\n#### Making the Chicken Balls:\n1. **Marinate Chicken**: In a bowl, combine the chicken pieces with ginger-garlic paste, soy sauce, salt, and black pepper. Let it marinate for at least 15-20 minutes.\n\n2. **Prepare Batter**: In another bowl, mix all-purpose flour and cornstarch. Add the beaten egg and enough water to make a smooth, thick batter.\n\n3. **Coat Chicken**: Dip each marinated chicken piece into the batter, ensuring it's fully coated.\n\n4. **Deep Fry**: Heat oil in a deep pan or kadai over medium heat. Once hot, deep fry the batter-coated chicken pieces until they are golden brown and crispy. Remove and drain on paper towels. Set aside.\n\n#### Preparing the Sauce:\n1. **Make Cornstarch Slurry**: In a small bowl, mix cornstarch with 2 tablespoons of water to make a smooth slurry. Set aside.\n\n2. **Saut\u00e9 Aromatics**: In a pan or wok, heat 2 tablespoons of oil over medium heat. Add chopped garlic, ginger, and green chili. Saut\u00e9 for about 30 seconds until fragrant.\n\n3. **Add Vegetables**: Add the white parts of the spring onions and diced bell peppers. Stir-fry for 2-3 minutes until they are slightly tender but still crisp.\n\n4. **Add Sauces and Spices**: Stir in soy sauce, tomato ketchup, red chili sauce (if using), vinegar, sugar, salt, and black pepper powder. Mix well.\n\n5. **Add Slurry**: Pour the cornstarch slurry into the pan, stirring continuously to avoid lumps. Cook the sauce until it thickens to your desired consistency.\n\n6. **Combine with Chicken Balls**: Add the fried chicken pieces to the sauce and toss gently to coat them evenly.\n\n7. **Garnish and Serve**: Garnish with the green parts of spring onions. Serve hot as an appetizer or with fried rice or noodles as a main dish.\n\n---\n\n## **Tips for Perfect Manchurian**\n\n1. **Ensure Crispiness**: Whether you're making vegetable or chicken Manchurian, ensure that the batter coating is thick enough to keep the balls crispy even after adding them to the sauce.\n\n2. **Frying Temperature**: Maintain the oil temperature around 350\u00b0F (175\u00b0C) for deep frying. If the oil is too hot, the coating may burn before the inside cooks; if too cold, the batter can become soggy.\n\n3. **Batter Consistency**: The batter should be thick enough to adhere to the vegetable florets or chicken pieces without dripping too much.\n\n4. **Customize Vegetables**: You can add other vegetables like carrots, beans, or mushrooms to the sauce for added texture and flavor.\n\n5. **Adjust Spice Levels**: Modify the amount of green chilies and red chili sauce according to your heat preference.\n\n6. **Serve Immediately**: Manchurian is best enjoyed hot for maximum crispiness. If you're preparing it in advance, consider frying the balls beforehand and reheating them briefly before adding to the sauce.\n\n---\n\nEnjoy your homemade Manchurian! Whether you choose the vegetarian or chicken version, this flavorful dish is sure to be a hit at your dining table.",
